<span id="freeTextContainer12669077803954588308">Ive just re-read this wonderful book and this time it resonates even more than it did when I read it to my 9 year old son. He doesn&apos;t remember it, and I think now that he was too young for it and another few years would have made tremendous difference to his understanding of the themes, but might also have made him wary of reading a story about talking clockwork toys. <br/>Now he&apos;s in his thirties, I think I&apos;ll give him a copy of his own.<br/>Everyone should read the story of the clockwork mouse and his c</span>
  <span id="freeText12669077803954588308" style="display:none">Ive just re-read this wonderful book and this time it resonates even more than it did when I read it to my 9 year old son. He doesn't remember it, and I think now that he was too young for it and another few years would have made tremendous difference to his understanding of the themes, but might also have made him wary of reading a story about talking clockwork toys. <br />Now he's in his thirties, I think I'll give him a copy of his own.<br />Everyone should read the story of the clockwork mouse and his child, the child who never gives up hope of a family and house of their own. Despite terrible mishaps, being caught in the middle of others' battles for territory (there's a lot about territory), and pursued by the ruthless Manny Rat, the two find friends as they journey, and all ends well, even for Manny Rat.<br />It's a story of quiet heroism, lively adventure, brilliantly plotted and very funny. <br />thank you Stephen for putting me in mind of it again.</span>
