<div id="review_1156385304" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1156385304" />
    <a title="Leonie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5133244-leonie"><img alt="Leonie" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1156385304?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leonie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leonie" href="/user/show/5133244-leonie">Leonie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780571202225" href="/book/show/382368.The_Mouse_and_His_Child">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5133244-leonie?shelf=children-s">children-s</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1156385304" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6162880838832734294">A pair of toy mice go on a quest for a home, pursued by an evil rat. I read a blog post about this which made me want to read it, and I thought it might be a good introduction to Hoban&apos;s adult books. It&apos;s a melancholy book with lots of death and I know it would have been too dark for me as a child. It&apos;s beautifully written and the helplessness and persistence of the mouse and his child give it the central effect of tenderness and wistfulness. There&apos;s some nice humorous bits about absurdist crow </span>
  <span id="freeText6162880838832734294" style="display:none">A pair of toy mice go on a quest for a home, pursued by an evil rat. I read a blog post about this which made me want to read it, and I thought it might be a good introduction to Hoban's adult books. It's a melancholy book with lots of death and I know it would have been too dark for me as a child. It's beautifully written and the helplessness and persistence of the mouse and his child give it the central effect of tenderness and wistfulness. There's some nice humorous bits about absurdist crow theatre etc. This did the epic journey genre really well for me; children's stories about toys are good like that, looking back, because you have to emphasise the characters' combination of helplessness with adventurousness and rely on happenstance to move them around. It makes the world seem big.<br /><br />Definitely the kind of children's book that adults wax lyrical about but isn't really for kids, though.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6162880838832734294" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

